Zach Hadel said something years ago that really opened my eyes to how ones outlook on art, or really any type of hobby, should be. He said basically
>You should never really do art or animation purely for money or popularity, enjoying the process should be the main reason
If you're not having fun while writing, then you shouldn't write. If your enjoyment from writing is purely the idea of seeing the number of comments, kudos and (you)s go up, then what's the point? Who cares if few people read what you wrote so long as you personally enjoyed the time you spent writing it?

I never thought genre indecision would give me an idea.
>Chapter one is character working as an accountant at a major company
>Chapter two is a continuation of chapter one, but now the character is a book keeper for some medieval guild that does the same thing as the major company

Alright, then I'll say it from my position as a nobody.
I used to dm tabletop games, and loved spending hours of time coming up with stories and worlds that got used and thrown away, because making interesting concepts and characters interact was genuinely enjoyable. Then I started story writing, dropping my random nonsensical garbage on random websites, before forgetting about the story and moving on at random. Now I intend to write a decent series of stories, and stick with them.
I have very few followers, and viewers, but I would still write even if not a single person read it, because I genuinely enjoy storytelling.

I encourage other people to do the same, because if your writing is trash, then it will not pay your bills, but if you stick with it you will eventually make content that people enjoy.

If we’re talking about general principles. You have to fail at immersing your audience, it doesn’t have to be “realistic” that’s boring and we fuck anthros here. But in some ways depending on the story beat you have to succeed in suspending disbelief just enough to allow the next phase. Which is getting them attached or otherwise emotionally invested in the stories, world, or characters. Sometimes step one is achieved -through- step two. But it’s important to compartmentalize your concepts to figure that out.

so in that sense, bad writing means that you’ve failed to do one or both of those things. don’t let that discourage you however, since a lot of what would make another guy not like your story might be really engaging or otherwise stimulating. But remember that if you read somebody’s criticism if you kinda see their point, then it’s probably worth at least mulling over if you want to improve in the gaps the critic pointed out. And on that same note, if somebody doesn’t like your story but you think that thing they don’t like is integral to the stories symbolism, plot, or theme, then by all means let them know your reasoning. if there’s something that they don’t see that they should have it’s either you just didn’t make it explicit enough- or they lack that perception that you have on it.

Anonymous Tue 09 Jan 2024 12:46:30 No.62453565 Report
Quoted By:
>>62452855
Exposition in a story is precarious in the first couple chapters, but once you make it a little ways in, it becomes a lot easier to add smoothly. There's two ways to go about it. The first is to have a character new to a setting, like a new employee who just flew up to a space station, and now has to learn all the procedures and nuances, so mentor characters will spend a lot of time explaining things to them.
The other way is to have a character familiar with a setting, such as a veteran soldier in a war story. Next to nothing will need to be explained to them, so the best way to go about this is to express the characters opinion on things regularly.
Always remember for the former option, when writing a mentor character, a trait that makes someone appear smart is the ability to explain complex things in easy to understand language.
